[2] Colorado
Date: Fri 26 Sep 2014
Source: Journal-Advocate [edited]
http://www.journal-advocate.com/sterling-local_news/ci_26608328/livestock-virus-spread-logan-county


Logan County [Colorado] has one location under active quarantine for vesicular stomatitis.

The latest update from the Colorado Department of Agriculture [CDA] on the statewide outbreak shows that 303 quarantines have been enacted since the livestock disease 1st hit Colorado this year [2014]; 177 of the quarantines have been released.

Logan County was listed as a newly affected county as of [10 Sep 2014] by the CDA, and that one quarantine is still in effect. Counties with the highest number of active quarantines include Larimer (48), Weld (24) and Boulder (20). Altogether, 10 Colorado counties have at least one quarantine still in effect.

While the number of new cases of VS continues to rise -- there were 6 new quarantine locations in the last week -- State Veterinarian Dr. Keith Roehr is hopeful that the spread of the disease is slowing.

"The good news is that the number of new cases are decreasing while the number of released quarantines are increasing; we believe that's a sign that we've hit the peak of this disease in Colorado for this year," he said in the CDA update.

VS is a virus that usually affects horses, mules, cattle, bison, sheep, goats, pigs, and camelids; human cases are possible but rare. The 2014 outbreak has affected mostly horses, cows have also tested positive in Larimer, Weld and Boulder counties.

[Byline: Sara Waite]

